snippet.textDisplay:
Tip for track stands: keep your shoulders parallel to the handle bar (so your shoulders are facing the same way your bars are) it will make you balance much better and you'll be able to be much more steady. And when it comes to your hands pull up with a hand when your falling towards (sounds obvious but you forget to do that when you're focused on balancing, u usually tend to push down instead which just makes you fall over). Keep your wheel turned quite sharply it will give you more balance. Have fun lol

For beginners try doing a track stand against a wall and once you get that try track standing against a wall and without putting your foot on the ground push away from the wall and continue cycling. It's easier than it sounds.
snippet.textOriginal:
Tip for track stands: keep your shoulders parallel to the handle bar (so your shoulders are facing the same way your bars are) it will make you balance much better and you'll be able to be much more steady. And when it comes to your hands pull up with a hand when your falling towards (sounds obvious but you forget to do that when you're focused on balancing, u usually tend to push down instead which just makes you fall over). Keep your wheel turned quite sharply it will give you more balance. Have fun lol

For beginners try doing a track stand against a wall and once you get that try track standing against a wall and without putting your foot on the ground push away from the wall and continue cycling. It's easier than it sounds.
